# Self-maintenance and drift control

Prevent drift between implementation, **project** documentation, and `.cursor` guidance.

## 1) No-drift requirement

When behavior, contracts, APIs, naming, or architecture changes:

- Update the project’s **canonical** docs (README, `docs/`, `design/`, or your chosen index such as `AGENTS.md` / `llms.txt`).
- Update application/runtime code in the same session when the change is user-visible or save-affecting.
- Update affected `.cursor/rules/**`, `.cursor/agents/**`, and `.cursor/skills/**` when they restate those contracts.
- Remove stale instructions instead of keeping old and new guidance in parallel.

## 2) When to audit

Run a focused consistency pass when changes touch:

- Core architecture or plugin/module boundaries
- Persistence, networking, or serialization formats
- Public event or message protocols
- Build, worker, or hot-reload lifecycle
- Non-obvious guardrails — keep a short rationale comment at the code site

## 3) Freshness metadata

Any updated rule, agent, or skill should refresh frontmatter **`lastReviewed`** (`YYYY-MM-DD`). New governance files should include it at creation.

## 4) Done criteria

- No stale implementation paths remain in touched areas.
- No contradictory guidance across `src/**`, canonical docs, and `.cursor/**`.
- Touched governance files include updated `lastReviewed`.
